# Supabase Email Confirmation Redirect Best Practices

## 1. Email Template

- Use the default template:
  ```html
  <a href="{{ .ConfirmationURL }}">Confirm your mail</a>
  ```
- Do **not** hardcode a `redirect_to` in the template unless you want a fixed redirect for all users/languages.

## 2. Registration Code (Frontend)

- When calling `supabase.auth.signUp`, always pass the correct `redirectTo` parameter for the user's language:
  ```js
  supabase.auth.signUp({
    email,
    password,
    options: {
      emailRedirectTo:
        "https://weddwebcom-git-beta-deploy-carles-projects-5a7d39cc.vercel.app/de/auth/confirm",
    },
  });
  ```
- Replace `/de/auth/confirm` with the correct language route for each user.

## 3. Supabase Dashboard Settings

- In **Authentication → URL Configuration**, add all possible callback/confirm URLs you use, e.g.:
  - https://weddwebcom-git-beta-deploy-carles-projects-5a7d39cc.vercel.app/en/auth/confirm
  - https://weddwebcom-git-beta-deploy-carles-projects-5a7d39cc.vercel.app/es/auth/confirm
  - ... (repeat for all supported languages)

## 4. How It Works

- The confirmation email will use the `redirectTo` you pass in your registration code.
- The user will be redirected to the correct `/auth/confirm` route for their language after clicking the email link.
- Your `/auth/confirm` route/component should handle the session/token and log the user in automatically.

## 5. Best Practice

- **Always pass the correct `redirectTo` in your registration code.**
- **Keep the email template as `{{ .ConfirmationURL }}` for flexibility.**
- **Add all used redirect URLs to Supabase dashboard.**

---

If you want to force a fixed redirect for all users, you can append `&redirect_to=...` in the template, but this is not recommended for multi-language apps.
